segments.text: at night, most of the time no preaching.
Alright, so when you came to the campus, you had no free time really.
That's right.
Unless you had a one hour break.
That first semester, did you go to some of the campus activities?
Like Yale practice?
No.
Did you go to football games?
Some of them.
Didn't have enough money to go to very many of them.
Describe a football day, a football Saturday here.
What time would you come to the campus?
Well, I'd just stay because we stayed at school until noon.
So we'd just stay over.
If my riders could find some way to get home, I'd just stay over.
So I wouldn't have to come back.
Now would you wear your dress uniform to class that morning or would you change clothes?
No, we just wore the uniform and wore it to the ball game.
And did the Corps march in in those days or just go straight to your seats in the game?
Oh, I think they marched in.
They marched in.
But the fact that I was not in the dormitory, I usually just went as a casual.
I didn't march into any of the football games at that time.
Now let's see, the head coach, was Coach Norton here then?
He was there.
The first, well I guess maybe for the whole time I was there.
Haskell, I think he was.
So you didn't eat much in the, in Sevesa?
Were the new core dorms being built yet?
They were started about my junior year, I guess it was, because our civil engineer classes went over a number of times.
That was an inspection trip, you know, to watch the dormitory being built.
Now, what was out there before?
What was on that piece of ground before they were built?
Nothing.
It was just vacant.
Was it used as a playground?
Oh, I think it was part of the pasture.
Part of the people that had the, you know, part of the departments that had horses and cows and this sort of thing.
I think it was.
Now, between what is now the core area and the Welborn Road,
there were lots of faculty houses, weren't there?
That's right.
On the campus?
Many of them.
And then at one, oh from the middle 30s on, the old big project houses were in there.
You know about those deals.
What did you and your buddies think about those project houses?
Well, you know, I didn't have any adverse feeling toward them.
It looked to me like there was an excellent way for those boys to stay in school, and it was.
That was a project of Mr. Dan Russell's.
He had that idea, and it was a super thing.
And the most dedicated Aggie former students that I know are the Project House graduates.
They're the ones most proud, most grateful.
Well, you know, they could bring stuff from home to play part of their board and room.
Of course, that was the idea of it.
Now, what was your routine for class?
Did you go to class every day?
And did you sit in a certain place up front or in the back?
I liked to sit up front.
I found out they didn't ask me so many questions when I sat up front.
Because the guys that were looking to get away from the questions always sat in the back.
And it was harder to go to sleep in the front, wasn't it?
Well, it was.
And Haskell, I was interested in going to school.
I wasn't interested in any horseplay and try to irritate the professors and this or that.
Some of them gave them a bad time.
But to answer your question, we had special seats we sat in.
And did you talk to the teachers much?
Did you go up after class?
Not a whole lot.
So you didn't go up and introduce yourself or anything like that?
Well, they all took place when you started.
You tried to make him know who you were.
What did you do to stay awake?
Because occasionally you must have gotten sleepy.
I don't remember that being a big problem.
The only problem that I remember it was was in the chemistry lecture hall where there was about 300, and it was done by Mr. Harrington, I believe.
M.T.
Harrington.
M.T.
Harrington.
The best lecturer that there ever was in the world.
Describe him.
Make believe I had never met him.
Well, he was tall and stately, and when he talked, he talked like this.
You could understand every word he said, all over the thing.
And he was so articulate and so...things were...
unraveled so smoothly the way he talked.
He always talked to you.
He didn't turn around and talk to the board and all this sort of thing.
Did he give the impression that he was proud to be a teacher?
He did.
Did he relate well to the students?
He sure did.
I believe that he was as universally liked as anybody that I had in the whole system.
Did he have a nickname?
I've never heard a nickname for him.
I don't remember one if you did.
When you got your grades that first semester, do you remember how you did?
In chemistry?
No, the whole semester.
Oh, I did art except on chemistry.
I don't think I made any A's.
I made a good many B's and two or three C's.
I made one D as I remember in English I think it was.
So I passed and that was, you know, I wasn't trying to be valedictorian or anything.
I was interested in getting through school.
During the day, if you wanted to go get a snack or anything or just take a break, where did you and your buddies go during the class day?
I don't remember doing that.
So you didn't go over to the YMCA or anything?
No.
Not me.
First place didn't have any money for it.
I didn't have any spending money, Haskell.
And so you weren't involved in any jokes or pranks?
Not really.
A good bull?
No.
I'm sure I missed some of that, but, you know, I was there to get my education and thought I was fortunate to be able to.
All right.
Did you go on a court trip?
No.
I went on one my senior year.
I went to Fort Worth.
And the only reason I did, because I had an aunt that lived in Fort Worth, I could spend the night with her.
How did you get up there?
Must have gone in my old car.
I can't remember.
No, I tell you, my senior year my dad traded that car off for a better Plymouth, and I think I went in that Plymouth because I didn't go on a court trip except in my senior year.
Did you take a load of guys with you?
No.
I took down my fiance.
She was one of my riders, too.
She and I started first grade together.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
And what was she doing on the campus?
She was a secretary at the extension service.
Okay.
She was a secretary to three ladies, three of those extension specialists.
And where were their offices?
What building?
It's what's the trigon now.
Okay.
That was the extension service.
Describe what was around the campus then, what areas were developed.
Well, Guyon Hall was there at that time.
Yes.
Hart Hall was there.
Mitchell Hall was there.
The trees were rather small, I guess.
Yes.
They had been planted some four or five years, most of them.
Railroad Station was a busy place.
It was.
And like you said, there were a lot of the residences on there.
Let me think.
But at Northgate, what was at Northgate?
Oh, there weren't but two or three things there.
Hollick Boot Shop was one.
Hollick made my boots.
Was Old Army Lou, he was in business already?
Yes.
Was the campus theater open yet?
I think it opened, if I'm not mistaken, while I was there.
And then there was a drive-in back there, you know, the open-air drive-in, where all those buildings and the high-rises and things are now.
Seemed to me like that's where that thing was.
But there weren't many houses on Southside and east of Texas Avenue, were there?
East of Texas?
No, not many.
There was a first court that was in Bryan was over there and it's called Bluetop Court.
You ever hear of that?
You're talking about Tourist Court?
Tourist Court.
What it was, it was an office and then each little cabin, and I don't know how many people, I guess one person would rent the cabin, and they all had blue roofs and they called it the Bluetop Court.
About where was that?
Well, it was about where, in the area where that shopping center is and the red, what's the fish place, red something?
Oh, Red Lobster.
Red Lobster.
Okay.
In that area.
Of course, none of that was there.
And when you started from Bryan to college,
You know where R.B.
Butler's construction office was?
And the big old two-story house that was the doctor's office, it's now a fraternity.
That was the last thing there was until you got out to where the Ramada Inn is now.
Nothing was in there pasturing.
And where University goes east, there was a grocery store right on the corner there called Macy's Grocery.
There wasn't anything on the other side.
And the University from there through the campus hadn't been built but a few years.
It was just a single concrete road.
What was the name of that street?
It wasn't University then.
What was it named?
I can't remember.
I'm trying to recall what it was.
I didn't tell you.
Now the streetcar, was it still operating?
No.
It had stopped?
Yeah.
So that, was there a bus?
Was there a city bus that went from?
No.
When I first remember, I ask them, Main Street of Bryan was Houston Highway.
It went straight on out and went down what's now, what do they call that street?
William J. Bryan?
No, over on the east side, I mean west side.
where Main goes on out.
That's the way the Houston Highway went and got to where the Farmer's Market is and it turned and went back to the railroad and went right down the railroad.
Wellborn was on the way to the Houston Highway.
And the depot, the railroad depot was right down in the middle of Bryan near the old courthouse.
Wasn't the depot down there?
You're talking about the Bryan Depot?
Uh-huh.
Yeah.
Yeah, it was just about where the Children's Museum is now.
Yeah, yeah.
Right along in there.
Now, how often did your family come to Bryan to buy groceries or anything?
Well, not regularly, but... Once a month?
Probably not over average of once a month.
My daddy had what he called a commissary to furnish the sharecroppers.
They would buy groceries and stuff and then pay them in the fall when they got their money in.
So a lot of the groceries that we had were bought that way.
We bought them out
had beans and sugar and rice and coffee and this sort of thing.
And he'd come to Brian to the wholesale place and get those and then furnish his sharecroppers with that.
Did your mother and other women do a lot of canning and preserving?
Oh, yes, sir.
We even canned beef.
My daddy would kill a beef.
and Mother would process it and we'd put it in tin cans and had a sealer for those cans, seal them and then put them in a pressure cooker and cook them and those things would last from then on.
Now was there a gin in Wheelock?
And then where did the corn get processed?
They had a mill in Wheelock that ground the corn and he ground it for
He took a toll out of it.
Nobody paid him.
Took a toll out of the corn.
And it was a blacksmith shop and a corn mill.
And he ground it as corn meal.
That's right.
Not flour.
Corn meal.
There was no flour made in Wheeler.
Now did y'all eat grits ever?
Not much.
See, I didn't know grits existed when I was a little kid.
Because that was something you had to buy.
Yeah.
We didn't need much that you had to buy.
When your family were going to kind of celebrate, what did they do?
Like did they ever take a vacation?
No.
Go fishing for fun or hunting for fun?
Once a year, several of the Wheelock families would go what they called camping.
Most of the time it was over on the Navasota River at one of the lakes and stayed two or three days.
And the ladies would take all the food and the men would catch a few fish.
But that was almost the vacations.
And those lakes were pretty small, weren't they?
Well, they were, but at the time
I don't know whether they were on private property or what, but everybody would come in and camp on them.
It didn't seem to make any difference.
You didn't have to get any permission.
All right.
So while you're doing all these tasks, your freshman year went pretty well.
And did you ever think about dropping out of school?
No.
Okay.
Never.
Then that first summer you worked part-time on the campus and took some extra courses.
Yes.
I liked those courses.
They went in a hurry, you know, six weeks
Then your sophomore year, was it very different from your freshman year?
Yeah.
You began to feel like you sort of belonged out there then, and then of course I think the course had got a little more difficult too.
Did you have any special courses that you recall that sophomore year that were important to you?
Well, it began to take a few things that were truly civil engineering.
It took some structures and things that rather than the arithmetic and the chemistry and the physics and this sort of thing.
Who were some of those engineering teachers that you remember?
Cy Sandstedt was one.
you know of him.
C.E.
Sanstead, I believe, is his name.
Joe Orr was another one.
Joe Orr taught surveying.
What was special about them?
Something special about Joe Orr, he'd take his surveying class out and do work, and I think he got paid for it.
I don't have no way of knowing, but I bet he did.
And then what was the head of... You said Sanstead.
What about him?
What was special about him?
Oh, he was not a flashy...
He was a sort of a reserved type teacher.
He wasn't...
Nothing really outstanding about him.
He was a good teacher.
Had the boys well at heart.
But I was trying to think what the other teacher's name was.
He's got a son who's a doctor here now.
What's his name?
C.E.
Department.
Doctor, doctor...
He's over here on North Avenue, I believe it is.
Doesn't ring a bell.
Doesn't ring a bell.
Who were your best buddies?
Well, mostly the boys that I worked with on, you know, the student labor.
Who?
I had one little old boy from Brady.
What was that little boy's name?
I'd have to get an old manual out over there and think.
I had another one that married a cousin of mine named Carter, Frank Carter, and incidentally he was with the Rudders Rangers that went in on D-Day.
He was badly injured and has since passed away.
In fact, I introduced him to his wife.
He married my cousin.
I was going to tell you a funny story, in fact, I thought this fellow's name that taught us part of our summer CE class.

We were out south of the campus and we did triangulation and we shot Polaris at night, which is the star of what you orient on, you know, and we'd get in the truck and some of us have to go way across the pasture to do our work and
Two or three of us would do the instrument work, and then the others would get up and they'd do it.
And while we were doing it, they'd either sit in the shade or whatever.
So this professor had told us, didn't want us laying around in the shade.
And he didn't want them without shirts on because of the sun, you know.
Well, one morning we went way off over there and one old boy named, boy and his name was Sharp.
I remember that, Chico Sharp.
He laid down on his stomach and his back was blistered from the sun.
He didn't think the professor would be over there.
And he carried a walking stick.
Well, that particular morning he walked over there.
And he took that stick and he rubbed it down Chico's back.
And Chico thought it was some of us.
And he said, you son of a bitch.
McNew.
McNew.
That's his name.
Lamar McNew's father.
Lamar McNew.
Yeah, yeah.
And Magnus said, Chico, get up and put your shirt on.
That's all he ever said at the time.
But you said, Mom, some funny stories.
Now that was a funny story.
That's good.
All right.
With your sophomore year, did you have any grade troubles or did things get better from there on?
I didn't have any problems sophomore year.
Did you go to more football games your sophomore year?
No, I just went to a bare number, you know.
I'd usually work on Saturday afternoon if I had the opportunity.
All right.
Where would you and your date go if you had a date on Saturday night?
Where did you all go?
We'd come to Bryan, go to a show.
Which, there were three downtown, three movies?
There were two at that time, as I remember.
Two?
What were they?
The Palace and The Queen.
Do you remember any special movies that you all saw?
I don't remember.
There was also a drug store on the corner and you could park and honk your horn and they'd come out and wait on you, you know.
And then there was a restaurant over on Bryan Street called Uncle Buck's.
The name was Buchanan.
If we didn't go to the drugstore, we'd go by there and get us a sandwich, and get a big old sandwich for 25 cents, and that was our dead meal.
And cut it in half?
Yeah.
At what time were you supposed to have her home?
They didn't give me any time.
I think I was pretty well trusted with that girl.
Her father owned a store there in Wheelock.
And did you all go to the same church?
We did.
Here on the campus, do you remember when you first went to Silver Taps?
I sure don't.
I didn't go to many, but I did
And I think the first one I went to was my freshman year, and the reason I did, one of the boys died that I was a pretty good friend with, one of my C.E.
buddies.
He got, what is this, what's this?
what the ailment was.
It's this thing sort of like flu and where you die from congestion and all this.
Pneumonia?
No.
It hit the campus right at Christmas.
Oh, oh, oh.
Influenza?
Yeah.
Some type of influenza.
Anyhow, he died, and I had been up in his room studying at times.
Scared the fool out of me, I'll tell you for sure.
And I went to his silver taps, and I think that's the first thing I ever went to.
Describe Silver Taps then compared to now in terms of how it was done.
Was it the same way?
Well, it was out in the area in front of the old administration building where Sully is, and they blew the taps from up on top of this administration building.
That's where the bugler was.
And everybody sat on the ground and that's where it took place.
Did everybody take it seriously?
Very seriously.
Nobody played any?
No, there wasn't any horseplay at all.
It was very quiet and when it was over they left without talking and very solemn.
What about Bonfire?
Do you remember?
Oh, I do.
I do.
Describe.
It was a bunch of trash.
That they gathered around the campus, didn't they?
That's right.
Gathered it up in the stores in boxes and barrels and it was over on what's now the drill field, the old, what do they call it?
Just the drill field.
Yeah.
It's got a name though now.
Oh, it's now named for the general.
Yeah.
Simpson.
Simpson.
That's where it was at that time.
Did you ever help?
No.
No.
Now, did they pick it up with the push carts from the railroad station?
I've heard that.
Yeah, or wagons or drug it, whatever.
You know, I've got two of those old carts out at my place.
Really?
Two of those old railroad things.
Oh my, how good, how good.
All right, what about muster?
Do you remember going to muster before World War II?
I don't really remember much about muster.
The first musters that I went to were after.
I truly don't remember any musters, and I don't know whether they had them or not.
Does anybody remember having muster?
Nobody does.
Just about like what you said, some of them say, I think they may have had one, but I'm not sure whether I went or not.
And I'm convinced that World War II changed that in turn.
I think it did.
I went to the one where Eisenhower was the speaker right after the war.
In fact, I've been to nearly every muster since the war.
During your years, describe the student body in general, the students that were here.
Where were they from?
What kind of families?
There was a lot of them from the farms and ranches.
I think I would just class them as, you know, normal boys of the time.
Some city boys, of course, and lots of farm boys.
About how many students had a car then?
Darn, none of them.
Oh, there wasn't a sprinkling of cars.
How many drove to the campus like you did?
A dozen?
A dozen?
Well, I wouldn't even guess because most of the people that parked in that parking lot were professors or staff of some sort.
And a bunch of them came from the project houses in buses or old trucks that had seats on them.
And that's where they'd come and let the boys off and then back out.
There was a sprinkling of day students that had cars.
I mean students that had cars.
But most everybody lived on campus.
Oh, yeah.
Well, there were a few off campuses, but not a lot of them.
And in terms of family income, there were lots of poor boys, but a few from well-to-do families?
There were.
Were there any students in your day that you all knew were from rich families?
Do you remember any of them?
A few.
Do you remember who they were by name?
No.
This boy that died came from a pretty well-off family, I remember that, from down in Pharr, Texas.
That's where he was from.
That's P-H-A-R-R. That's right.
And in terms of their national background, there were
German boys and Czech boys.
But you know we didn't have a lot of these foreigners like we got now.
We had what the United States had as foreigners, but none of the, gosh there wasn't any Japanese or Chinese to mount anything.
Were there some Hispanic, American-Hispanic boys?
There were, there were.
And how was everybody treated, the students?
I assume with much respect.
Did it matter?
Were you treated any special way because your father was a farmer?
I doubt it.
I doubt it.
I think most of them were treated however they were able to place themselves in society.
I remember Reveille.
Oh, describe.
I got a picture of her in my annual.
I just saw it this morning.
Because Reveley was new then, wasn't it?
The little cur dog, yeah.
In fact, I think she came there maybe either while I was there or just before.
Describe that dog.
Little fat cur dog about that long and about that big around.
Little brownish-gray dog.
And she just won.
